        <briefdescription>
<para>\par \b Module Contract\/ \:</para>
<para>\par \b Purpose\/ \:  Define the LineMetadata schema — a Pydantic model for paragraph/line-level metadata (paragraph type, page number, line number) with extra attributes support. </para>
        </briefdescription>
        <detaileddescription>
<para>\par \b Scope\/ \:  Document line/paragraph metadata model. \par \b Input\/ \:  None (standalone model with Extra.allow). \par \b Output\/ \:  Pydantic BaseModel <computeroutput>LineMetadata</computeroutput> with paragraph_type, page_id, line_id + extra fields. \par \b Links\/ \:  [USES_API(7): pydantic.BaseModel, pydantic.Extra] \par \b Invariants\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>page_id &gt;= 0.</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>paragraph_type is always a non-empty string (e.g., &quot;raw_text&quot;, &quot;header&quot;, &quot;list_item&quot;).</para>
</listitem><listitem><para>Extra fields preserved for format-specific metadata. \par \b Rationale\/ \:</para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
<para>Q: Why Extra.allow for line metadata? A: Different parsers attach different metadata (heading levels, indentation, list numbering). Extra.allow prevents loss. \par \b Changes\/ \:</para>
<para>LAST_CHANGE: [v1.0.0 – Initial creation with semantic markup] \par \b Module Map\/ \:</para>
<para>CLASS 9[Line/paragraph metadata with extra attributes] =&gt; LineMetadata \par \b Use Cases\/ \:</para>
<para><itemizedlist>
<listitem><para>[LineMetadata]: StructureExtractor =&gt; AnnotateParagraph =&gt; PassToTreeNode </para>
</listitem></itemizedlist>
</para>
        </detaileddescription>
